## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a scalable, per-tenant policy engine across REST/GraphQL/gRPC with edge latency constraints and safe rollouts.

## Key Concepts

- Policy language extension (YAML-like)
- Central per-tenant policy registry with TTL
- Edge enforcement using token buckets and Redis-backed state
- Cross-protocol adapters aligned to a canonical EndpointId
- Canary rollouts and safe migration paths

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudo policy evaluation sketch
function canServe(tenantId, endpointKey) {
  const bucket = getBucketFromRedis(tenantId, endpointKey);
  if (bucket.tokens > 0) {
    bucket.tokens--;
    return true;
  }
  return false;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you resolve conflicting quotas across overlapping contracts?
- How would you monitor, alert, and roll back policy changes during canaries?

## Why This Is Asked
This question probes cross-protocol data governance: masking at the boundary across REST, GraphQL, and gRPC, driven by per-tenant OpenAPI contracts. It tests how to derive and enforce field visibility, roll out changes safely, and audit policy drift.

## Key Concepts
- Per-tenant field-level visibility across protocols
- Contract-driven masking rules derived from OpenAPI
- Central registry (Redis) for tenant/resource visibility
- Canary rollouts and rollout safety across services

## Code Example

```javascript
function maskVisible(obj, tenantId, contract) {
  if (Array.isArray(obj)) return obj.map(v => maskVisible(v, tenantId, contract));
  if (obj === null || typeof obj !== 'object') return obj;
  const out = {};
  const allowed = contract?.visibleFields || [];
  for (const [k, v] of Object.entries(obj)) {
    out[k] = allowed.includes(k) ? v : 'REDACTED';
  }
  return out;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test contract drift and automated rollback when masking changes break clients?
- What metrics would you collect to detect masking-related regressions across REST, GraphQL, and gRPC?

## Why This Is Asked
