## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to coordinate multi-protocol schemas, feature flag strategy, and safe evolution without breaking clients.

## Key Concepts

- Single source of truth for schemas across REST, GraphQL, and gRPC
- Per-protocol adapters that conditionally expose fields
- Feature flag architecture and tenant isolation
- Consistent error envelope across protocols

## Code Example

```javascript
// REST adapter sketch (Node.js)
if (featureFlagEnabled('priority', tenantId)) {
  resp.priority = task.priority
} else {
  delete resp.priority
}
```

```graphql
# SDL snippet
type Task {
  id: ID!
  title: String!
  priority: Priority
}
```

```proto
// proto.js-like sketch
message Task {
  string id = 1;
  string title = 2;
  optional Priority priority = 3; // present only if flag enabled per tenant
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you test rollout and rollback of the feature flag across all three protocols?
- How do you handle schema drift if the flag is rolled back mid-deployment?

## Performance Characteristics

**REST**: HTTP/1.1 overhead ~1KB per request, limited to one request per connection. Best for CRUD operations with ~95% cacheability.

**GraphQL**: Single endpoint reduces network overhead, but query complexity can cause N+1 problems. Apollo Engine shows 30-40% payload reduction vs REST.

**gRPC**: HTTP/2 multiplexing enables concurrent streams. Protocol Buffers reduce payload size by 60-80% vs JSON.

## Use Case Scenarios

```typescript
// REST - Public API
GET /api/users/123/posts

// GraphQL - Mobile app with data requirements
query GetUserPosts($userId: ID!) {
  user(id: $userId) {
    name
    posts(first: 10) {
      title
      comments(count: 3)
    }
  }
}

// gRPC - Internal microservice
service UserService {
  rpc GetUser(GetUserRequest) returns (UserResponse);
}
```

## Error Handling & Authentication

- **REST**: HTTP status codes (200, 404, 500) + JWT/OAuth2
- **GraphQL**: Single 200 response with error payload + JWT
- **gRPC**: Status codes (OK, NOT_FOUND, INTERNAL) + SSL/TLS with token-based auth

## Real-World Applications

- Netflix: REST for public APIs, gRPC for internal services
- GitHub: GraphQL v4 API (95% faster than REST v3)
- Uber: gRPC for microservices communication (30% latency reduction)

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design a cross-protocol contract gateway with idempotency, migrations, and end-to-end coordination in a fintech context.

## Key Concepts
- Canonical contract that drives REST, GraphQL, and gRPC surfaces
- Idempotency using a distributed correlationId in Redis or similar
- Durable outbox for cross-protocol retries
- Versioned migrations with contract testing across protocols

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo: idempotent create payment entry
async function handleCreatePaymentREST(req) {
  const cid = req.headers['Correlation-Id'] || req.query.correlationId;
  const existing = await outbox.findByCorrelationId(cid);
  if (existing) return existing.response;
  const hop1 = await graphqlClient.mutate('createPayment', req.body);
  await outbox.save({correlationId: cid, response: hop1});
  return {paymentId: hop1.data.createPayment.id};
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test cross-protocol migrations without breaking consumers?
- How do you handle partial failures between REST and gRPC during a write?

