## Why This Is Asked

This question evaluates practical cache invalidation strategies in multi-region Redis deployments, testing understanding of versioned cache keys, cross-region synchronization, and TTL management. It also assesses knowledge of Redis pub/sub versus keyspace notifications and write-through caching trade-offs.

## Key Concepts

- Versioned cache keys with TTL management
- Cross-region invalidation patterns
- Redis pub/sub vs keyspace notifications
- Atomic operations and consistency guarantees
- Write-through vs write-behind caching strategies

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudo: bumpVersion(id)
const newVer = await redis.incr(`product:${id}:ver`);
await redis.publish('cache:invalidate', JSON.stringify({id, ver: newVer}));
```

```javascript
// Pseudo: getCache(id)
const currentVer = await redis.get(`product:${id}:ver`);
const cached = await redis.get(`product:${id}:v${currentVer}`);
if (!cached) {
  // Cache miss - refresh from source
  const data = await fetchFromDatabase(id);
  await redis.setex(`product:${id}:v${currentVer}`, 120, JSON.stringify(data));
  return data;
}
return JSON.parse(cached);
```

## Why This Is Asked
Tests design of robust, multi-tenant cache invalidation with Redis and Memcached, covering versioning, streams, stampede protection, and testability.

## Key Concepts
- Versioned per-tenant keys
- Redis Streams or Pub/Sub for invalidation
- Stampede protection via short TTLs and mutexes
- Cross-service invalidation consistency
- Observability and test plans

## Code Example
```javascript
function publishInvalidation(tenantId, itemId, ver){
  redis.xadd(`cache_invalidate:tenant:${tenantId}`, '*', 'item', itemId, 'ver', ver);
}
async function readItem(tenantId, itemId){
  const v = await redis.get(`tenant:${tenantId}:item:${itemId}:v`);
  const cached = await redis.get(`tenant:${tenantId}:item:${itemId}:data`);
  if (cached && v === latestVersionFromStore(itemId)){
    return JSON.parse(cached);
  } else {
    const fresh = await fetchFromStore(tenantId, itemId);
    await redis.set(`tenant:${tenantId}:item:${itemId}:data`, JSON.stringify(fresh));
    await redis.set(`tenant:${tenantId}:item:${itemId}:v`, latestVersionFromStore(itemId));
    return fresh;
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would this adapt to Memcached-only environments?
- How would you measure correctness and latency impact?
- How would you handle cascading invalidations across services?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests versioned cache invalidation across tenants, balancing consistency and hot-path performance.

## Key Concepts
- Per-tenant, per-product cache keys with a shared version
- Invalidation via version bump and pub/sub
- Stampede protection with distributed locking
- TTL-based fallback for eventual consistency

## Code Example
```javascript
// Python-like pseudocode in JS terms; Redis calls shown for clarity
async function updateProduct(pId, price, stock){
  const ver = await redis.incr(`product:${pId}:version`);
  await redis.publish(`prod_updated:${pId}`, String(ver));
}
async function getProductForTenant(pId, tenantId){
  const ver = await redis.get(`product:${pId}:version`);
  const cacheKey = `cache:prod:${pId}:tenant:${tenantId}:v${ver}`;
  let data = await redis.get(cacheKey);
  if(data) return JSON.parse(data);
  const lock = `lock:cache:${pId}:${tenantId}`;
  const ok = await redis.set(lock, '1', 'NX', 'EX', 5);
  if(ok){
    data = await loadFromDB(pId); // resp: price, stock, etc.
    await redis.set(cacheKey, JSON.stringify(data), 'EX', 60);
    await redis.del(lock);
  } else {
    await sleep(50);
    return getProductForTenant(pId, tenantId);
  }
  return data;
}
```

