Use a stable, deterministic hash of the deviceId to map devices to shards, leveraging a virtual node ring to tolerate node movement. For roaming devices, route new events to the target shard while maintaining a short reconciliation window to ensure no events are lost during migration.

## Code Examples

```javascript
// 1) ShardRouter interface
interface ShardRouter {
  route(deviceId: string): string;
  getPhysicalShard(virtualNode: string): string;
}

// 2) deviceToShard mapper with consistent hashing
class ConsistentHashRouter implements ShardRouter {
  private ring: Map<number, string> = new Map();
  private sortedKeys: number[] = [];
  private readonly vNodes: number = 150;

  constructor(private shards: string[]) {
    this.buildRing();
  }

  private buildRing(): void {
    for (const shard of this.shards) {
      for (let i = 0; i < this.vNodes; i++) {
        const hash = this.hash(`${shard}:vn:${i}`);
        this.ring.set(hash, shard);
      }
    }
    this.sortedKeys = Array.from(this.ring.keys()).sort((a, b) => a - b);
  }

  private hash(key: string): number {
    let h = 2166136261;
    for (const c of key) {
      h ^= c.charCodeAt(0);
      h = (h * 16777619) >>> 0;
    }
    return h;
  }

  route(deviceId: string): string {
    const hash = this.hash(deviceId);
    const idx = this.sortedKeys.findIndex(k => k >= hash);
    const key = idx === -1 ? this.sortedKeys[0] : this.sortedKeys[idx];
    return this.ring.get(key)!;
  }

  getPhysicalShard(virtualNode: string): string {
    return this.ring.get(this.hash(virtualNode))!;
  }
}

// 3) CrossDCReplicator outline
class CrossDCReplicator {
  constructor(
    private localRouter: ShardRouter,
    private remoteDC: string,
    private replicationFactor: number = 2
  ) {}

  async replicate(event: DeviceEvent): Promise<void> {
    const primaryShard = this.localRouter.route(event.deviceId);
    await Promise.all([
      this.writeLocal(event, primaryShard),
      this.replicateToRemote(event, primaryShard)
    ]);
  }

  private async writeLocal(event: DeviceEvent, shard: string): Promise<void> {
    console.log(`Writing event ${event.id} to shard ${shard}`);
  }

  private async replicateToRemote(event: DeviceEvent, primaryShard: string): Promise<void> {
    console.log(`Replicating event ${event.id} to ${this.remoteDC}`);
  }

  async handleRoamingMigration(
    deviceId: string,
    fromShard: string,
    toShard: string
  ): Promise<void> {
    await this.ensureRoamingSync(deviceId, fromShard, toShard);
    await this.finalizeMigration(deviceId, toShard);
  }

  private async ensureRoamingSync(deviceId: string, from: string, to: string): Promise<void> {
    console.log(`Roaming sync: ${deviceId} from ${from} → ${to}`);
  }

  private async finalizeMigration(deviceId: string, toShard: string): Promise<void> {
    console.log(`Migration finalized: ${deviceId} → ${toShard}`);
  }
}
```

## Trade-offs: Roaming Latency vs. Cross-DC Consistency

| Concern | Low Latency Approach | High Consistency Approach |
|---------|---------------------|---------------------------|
| **Write path** | Write to local DC, async replicate | Sync write to majority DCs |
| **Roaming events** | Dual-write window with dedup | Sequential migration with pause |
| **Consistency** | Eventual (read-your-writes) | Strong (causal ordering) |
| **Complexity** | Idempotency layer required | Distributed transactions |

**Recommendation**: For fleet telematics, prioritize availability and low latency with eventual consistency. Use idempotent event IDs and a 30-60 second reconciliation window to absorb migration lag. Strong consistency is rarely needed for telemetry data.

